translatedContent: The sweeps can be configured with a sweep configuration (defaulted to `sweep-config.yaml`) and base configuration (defaulted to `config.yaml`). originContent: This repo is intended to eventually be used as a library. All source files should be under the `pokemonred_puffer` directory. If you want to add a module with a `__main__`, feel free to, but under the `pokemonred_puffer` directory. Afterwards, you should be to run your main with `python3 -m pokemonred_puffer.<your-module>`

originContent: Within the `pokemonred_puffer` directory there are the following files and directories:
translatedContent: Within the `pokemonred_puffer` directory there are the following files and directories:

originContent: - `policies`: A directory for different policies to run the model with.
translatedContent: - `policies`: A directory for different policies to run the model with.

originContent: - `rewards`: A directory of `gym.Env` classes that keep track of rewards for a `RedGymEnv` (gym environment for Pokemon Red) object
translatedContent: - `rewards`: A directory of `gym.Env` classes that keep track of rewards for a `RedGymEnv` (gym environment for Pokemon Red) object

originContent: - `wrappers`: A directory of wrappers that you may want to use, e.g. logging to the [Pokemon Red Map Visualizer](https://pwhiddy.github.io/pokerl-map-viz/).
translatedContent: - `wrappers`: A directory of wrappers that you may want to use, e.g. logging to the [Pokemon Red Map Visualizer](https://pwhiddy.github.io/pokerl-map-viz/).

originContent: - `eval.py` - For generating visualizations for logging during training.
translatedContent: - `eval.py` - For generating visualizations for logging during training.

originContent: - `kanto_map_dsv.png` - A high resolution map of the Kanto region.

originContent: For simple changes, you can update `config.yaml` directly. `config.yaml` has a few important rules. For `wrappers`, `rewards` and `policies`, the wrapper, reward or policy _must_ be keyed by `module_name.class_name`. These sections can hold multiple types of `wrappers`, `rewards` or `policies`. The general layout is `label : arguments for the class`. This is until a better way with less indirection is figured out.
translatedContent: For simple changes, you can update `config.yaml` directly. `config.yaml` has a few important rules. For `wrappers`, `rewards` and `policies`, the wrapper, reward or policy _must_ be keyed by `module_name.class_name`. These sections can hold multiple types of `wrappers`, `rewards` or `policies`. The general layout is `label : arguments for the class`. This is until a better way with less indirection is figured out.

originContent: To add wrappers, add a new class that inherits from `gym.Wrapper` to the `wrappers` directory. Then update the `wrappers` section of `config.yaml`. The wrappers wrap the base environment in order, from top to bottom. The wrappers list is _not_ keyed by the class path. It is a unique name that distinguishes the collection of wrappers.
translatedContent: To add wrappers, add a new class that inherits from `gym.Wrapper` to the `wrappers` directory. Then update the `wrappers` section of `config.yaml`. The wrappers wrap the base environment in order, from top to bottom. The wrappers list is _not_ keyed by the class path. It is a unique name that distinguishes the collection of wrappers.

originContent: To add rewards, add a new class to the `rewards` directory. Then update the `rewards` section of `config.yaml`. A reward section is keyed by the class path.
translatedContent: To add rewards, add a new class to the `rewards` directory. Then update the `rewards` section of `config.yaml`. A reward section is keyed by the class path.

originContent: To add policies, add a new class to the `policies` directory. Then update the `policies` section of `config.yaml`. A policy section is keyed by the class path. It is assumed that a recurrent policy will live in the same module as the policy it wraps.
translatedContent: To add policies, add a new class to the `policies` directory. Then update the `policies` section of `config.yaml`. A policy section is keyed by the class path. It is assumed that a recurrent policy will live in the same module as the policy it wraps.
